  "prompt": "What is the integration of \u221asinx?",
  "response": "The integral of \\(\\sqrt{\\sin x}\\) with respect to \\(x\\) does not have an expression in terms of elementary functions (such as polynomials, exponentials, logarithms, trigonometric functions, etc.). Instead, it is expressed using special functions, specifically the **Gaussian hypergeometric function** \\({}_2F_1\\).\n\n### Detailed Explanation\n\nTo evaluate the integral:\n\n\\[\n\\int \\sqrt{\\sin x} \\, dx\n\\]\n\nwe can proceed with the following substitution:\n\n1. **Substitution:** Let \\( t = \\cos x \\).\n   - Then, \\( dt = -\\sin x \\, dx \\), which implies \\( dx = -\\frac{dt}{\\sqrt{1 - t^2}} \\).\n\n2. **Rewriting the Integral:**\n   - The integral becomes:\n     \\[\n     \\int \\sqrt{\\sin x} \\, dx = -\\int \\frac{(1 - t^2)^{1/4}}{\\sqrt{1 - t^2}} \\, dt = -\\int (1 - t^2)^{-1/4} \\, dt\n     \\]\n   \n3. **Expressing in Terms of Hypergeometric Function:**\n   - The integral \\(\\int (1 - t^2)^{-1/4} \\, dt\\) can be expressed using the hypergeometric function \\({}_2F_1\\):\n     \\[\n     \\int (1 - t^2)^{-1/4} \\, dt = t \\cdot {}_2F_1\\left(\\frac{1}{2}, \\frac{1}{4}; \\frac{3}{2}; t^2\\right) + C\n     \\]\n   \n4. **Final Expression:**\n   - Substituting back \\( t = \\cos x \\), we obtain:\n     \\[\n     \\int \\sqrt{\\sin x} \\, dx = -\\cos x \\cdot {}_2F_1\\left(\\frac{1}{2}, \\frac{1}{4}; \\frac{3}{2}; \\cos^2 x\\right) + C\n     \\]\n   - Here, \\( C \\) is the constant of integration.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThus, the integral of \\(\\sqrt{\\sin x}\\) is expressed in terms of the Gaussian hypergeometric function:\n\n\\[\n\\int \\sqrt{\\sin x} \\, dx = -\\cos x \\cdot {}_2F_1\\left(\\frac{1}{2}, \\frac{1}{4}; \\frac{3}{2}; \\cos^2 x\\right) + C\n\\]\n\nwhere \\( {}_2F_1 \\) is the hypergeometric function and \\( C \\) is the constant of integration.",
